[2] Ukraine (Western)
Date: Fri 29 Jul 2011
Source: Komsomolskaya Pravda [in Russian, trans. Mod.CP, edited]
http://kp.ua/daily/281811/292875/


At the end of July [2011], the press service of the Ministry of Health
of Ukraine reported 10 cases of measles in the village of Lutsk
[Lutsky region]. Of those, 7 were children under 14 years, one a
teenager, and 2 were adults.

To prevent the spread of measles, the 25 other children in the village
were vaccinated as a precautionary measure. In order to prevent
further spread of measles virus infection, the vaccination programme
of the West Ukraine oblast will be revised. According to doctors at
Lutsky Central Hospital, the typical serious complications of measles
in unvaccinated individuals are an inflammation of the lungs and
encephalitis. At the present time, more and more adults are succumbing
to this childhood illness.

In a measles outbreak in the Volynsk oblast in 2009, about 1000 people
were struck down by the disease. Measles infection is often
sufficiently serious to require rest and isolation, but complications
of the disease are rare -- generally affecting only one in several
thousand cases -- according to the chief pediatric infectious disease
specialist Sergei Kramarev of the Ministry of Health.

In Ukraine, a mass measles vaccination campaign was initiated in 2009
using a commercially produced vaccine funded by the international
community. But the quality of the vaccine was suspect following the
deaths of some adults in Krsnyarks, and the vaccine was withdrawn and
destroyed. As a consequence, more than half the population has
remained unvaccinated. A replacement vaccine will entail significant
additional expense and will not be available for more than a month.

