[5] USA (IN)
Date: Fri 29 Jul 2011
Source: The Journal Gazette [edited]
http://healthmap.org/ln.php?802265&u3409


The 37-day measles outbreak that spawned 14 confirmed cases across 2
northeast Indiana counties has officially ended, the Indiana State
Department of Health said. Noble County Public Health Nurse Cheryl
Munson said the outbreak would be considered over if no new cases had
been reported by Tue [26 Jul 2011]. Lab reports returned Friday [29
Jul 2011] confirmed her earlier prediction. According to Munson, the
testing consisted of analyzing 268 blood samples and 33 nasal
specimens. 14 returned positive, Munson said, but none were new
cases.

The outbreak "is officially over since no new cases have been reported
in the last 21 days," Munson said. The initial outbreak began 20 Jun
2011 and sparked 12 cases in Noble County and 2 cases in LaGrange
County. According to the Indiana Department of Health, the maximum
time it takes for an unvaccinated person to develop measles symptoms
is 21 days. Munson said her ending estimate was modeled after that
time frame, with the last reported exposure being 21 days prior to
Tuesday [26 Jul 2011].

The 1st case originated with an unvaccinated Noble County resident who
contracted the respiratory disease on an international trip in
mid-June 2011. The infected person had "close contact" with other
members of his community upon returning stateside, Indiana Health
Commissioner Gregory Larkin told The Journal Gazette last month [June
2011]. In response to the resident's interactions and the illness'
highly contagious nature, state health officials in late June 2011
warned that Allen, DeKalb, Elkhart, Kosciusko, LaGrange, Steuben and
Whitley counties could all be affected.

[Byline: Patrick Svitek]

