[7] USA (PA)
Date: Thu 28 Jul 2011
Source: The Mercury [edited]
http://pottsmerc.com/articles/2011/07/28/news/doc4e31d4867cae4597504457.txt


The Montgomery County Health Department issued an advisory that a
county resident who traveled to Nigeria in Africa has contracted a
case of measles. Several people who came in contact with the infected
individual are being evaluated.

"County investigators and staff from local health care facilities have
contacted a number of individuals who might have been exposed to
measles to assess each person's risk. While most of those exposed have
been found to be immune to the disease, some non-immune persons have
been asked to stay home until they are cleared of risk," a press
release from the Health Department read. "At this time, there is no
evidence that this case is related to the measles cluster in Berks
County."

The infected individual visited 3 locations in the county, and the
Health Department is warning area residents who may have been at those
locations at the same time to be aware of possible symptoms of
measles. "Because measles is spread by infected droplets during
sneezing or coughing, by contaminated objects, and by direct contact
with nasal or throat secretions of infected persons, exposures may
have occurred at these places," the Health Department said. "The
measles virus resides in the mucus in the nose and throat of infected
people. When they sneeze or cough, droplets spray into the air, and
the droplets remain active and contagious on infected surfaces for up
to 2 hours."

The infected individual visited the following locations at the
specified times:
- Victory Christian Fellowship at 2650 Audubon Road in Lower
Providence on 24 Jul 2011 from 12:30 p.m. to 3:30 p.m.
- Mercy Suburban Hospital Emergency Department on DeKalb Pike in East
Norriton between 10 p.m. 26 Jul 2011 and 5 a.m. 27 Jul 2011
- Whitemarsh Medical Services at 1107 Bethlehem Pike, Suite 210,
Flourtown, on 27 Jul 2011 between 3:50 p.m. and 6:10 p.m.

