[9] New Zealand (Auckland)
Date: Thu 28 Jul 2011
Source: Times online [edited]
http://www.times.co.nz/cms/news/2011/07/outbreak_of_measles_set_to_escalate.php


Parents need to be aware of the risks of taking unimmunised children
into public places over the school holidays. There are 90 confirmed
measles cases in Auckland [compared with 76 on Mon 25 Jul 2011 -- see
preceding report. -- Mod.CP], and more are expected following the
results of laboratory tests. "It's showing no signs of coming under
control," says Dr Richard Hoskins, medical officer of health. "It's
continuing to spread. That number looks like it's going to get a lot
bigger."

Dr Hoskins says parents who have chosen not to immunise their children
need to ensure they are kept away from public places over the
holidays. "You need to be not exposing your kid to places where they
might pick up measles, not only to protect your child but to stop your
child from getting and spreading it."

A student from Wakaaranga School, Farm Cove, contracted the disease a
few weeks ago. The pupil was quarantined along with dozens of other
unimmunised children in the last week of term, as well as those who
could not produce an immunisation certificate. "So far, we haven't got
any cases that are linked back to the school or that kid," says Dr
Hoskins. "It's 3 weeks since then, so we would expect to have been
notified of any cases."

As of yesterday [27 Jul 2011], the total number of Aucklanders with
confirmed measles was 90, and 13 contacts were in quarantine. Possible
cases have been reported in other parts of the country, but none have
been proven. Dr Hoskins says people need to stay in quarantine for 14
days from the time they come in contact with an infectious person.
"The only way to prevent it if it's circulating in a community is to
be immune to it yourself. The best way to do that is to have
age-appropriate immunisation."

All measles outbreaks in the past few years can be traced to people
bringing the disease in from overseas. "I'm not talking about people
who are immigrating to New Zealand or tourists," says Dr Hoskins. "I'm
talking about New Zealanders who have gone overseas and brought it
back with them. I wouldn't be surprised to find families that have
travelled out of Auckland and developed measles have spread it to
other parts of New Zealand, or to other places."

[Byline: Rebecca Gardiner]

